Some more comments:

+ What are you going to fill the forms with?
+ Be careful.  Wanton POSTing of forms will likely get you into hot 
water with webmasters.  The lads here that run the crawls have run into 
issues where submissions of empty forms using GET method have unforeseen 
side-effects: e.g. the sending of emails filling inboxes, adding rows to 
databases, etc. (The crawling lads can tell it better than I).
+ I&#39;m not sure how much exercise the credential system in Heritrix has 
had.  We know it works for basic logins -- Part of the Heritrix 
self-test requires passing a few authentication challenge types -- but 
this recent Andrzej Bialecki mail to the nutch-user list makes an 
interesting general comment on getting past forms.

Good luck,
St.Ack


Michael Stack wrote:
&gt;
&gt; blah_1977 wrote:
&gt;
&gt;&gt; OK, I see the Credential-related classes. Now in the CredentialStore
&gt;&gt; class there is a create() method. Can I use this method to
&gt;&gt; programmatically create a Credential during the course of crawling
&gt;&gt; when I discover forms whose submission needs an HTTP POST?
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Thats an interesting idea. 
&gt;
&gt; A few points:
&gt;
&gt; + Before heritrix processes an URL, we check for preconditions such as 
&gt; DNS or robots.txt.  If absent, the URL is put aside until the 
&gt; preconditions are met.  The credentials system leverages this 
&gt; facility.  An operator fills in credentials for servers that require 
&gt; login.  As heritrix encounters new hosts, along w/ DNS and robots.txt, 
&gt; it checks if it has credentials to offer for the newly-discovered 
&gt; host.  If it has, as a precondition, it first runs the supplied 
&gt; credentials.  Your suggestion, its likely, would be adding credentials 
&gt; -- and a precondition -- after we&#39;ve already begun crawling a 
&gt; particular host.  The next URL from the host to which credentials have 
&gt; been programmatically attached will be put aside until the credentials 
&gt; have been run.  Adding a precondition after we&#39;ve already started in 
&gt; on a host should work -- after-all, robots.txt expires and we handle 
&gt; that gracefully -- but be warned there may be kinks/assumptions in 
&gt; here that need modification.
&gt; + Be forewarned that it can be trying tracing the scheduling and the 
&gt; running of credentials since state spans more than a single-run down 
&gt; the processor-chain.  You have heritrix up in a debuggger?  And 6.2.3 
&gt; Credentials in the user manual, 
&gt; http://crawler.archive.org/articles/user_manual/config.html#submodules, 
&gt; shows how to enable credential logging.
&gt;
&gt; Good luck and let us know how it goes for you.  Ask questions up here 
&gt; if you run into blocks or if you need changes made in heritrix core.
&gt;
&gt; St.Ack
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; --- In archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com 
&gt;&gt; &lt;mailto:archive-crawler%40yahoogroups.com&gt;, Michael Stack &lt;stack@...&gt; 
&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; Heritrix only does HTTP POST when configured to supply login
&gt;&gt; &gt; credentials. See the 6.2.3. Credentials section on this page
&gt;&gt; &gt; 
&gt;&gt; http://crawler.archive.org/articles/user_manual/config.html#submodules, 
&gt;&gt; &lt;http://crawler.archive.org/articles/user_manual/config.html#submodules,&gt; 
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; in particular 6.2.3.2. HTML Form POST or GET. Otherwise its HTTP
&gt;&gt; &gt; GET&#39;ing all day long.
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt; &gt; St.Ack
&gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  


