Thats an interesting idea.&nbsp; &lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
A few points:&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;br&gt;
+ Before heritrix processes an URL, we check for preconditions such as
DNS or robots.txt.&nbsp; If absent, the URL is put aside until the
preconditions are met.&nbsp; The credentials system leverages this
facility.&nbsp; An operator fills in credentials for servers that require
login.&nbsp; As heritrix encounters new hosts, along w/ DNS and robots.txt,
it checks if it has credentials to offer for the newly-discovered
host.&nbsp; If it has, as a precondition, it first runs the supplied
credentials.&nbsp; Your suggestion, its likely, would be adding credentials
-- and a precondition -- after we&#39;ve already begun crawling a
particular host.&nbsp; The next URL from the host to which credentials have
been
programmatically attached will be put aside until the credentials have
been run.&nbsp; Adding a precondition after we&#39;ve already started in on a
host should work -- after-all, robots.txt expires and we handle that
gracefully -- but be warned there may be kinks/assumptions in here that
need modification. &lt;br&gt;
+ Be forewarned that it can be trying tracing the scheduling and the
running of credentials since state spans more than a single-run down
the processor-chain.&nbsp; You have heritrix up in a debuggger?&nbsp; And 6.2.3
Credentials in the user manual,
